<html>
<body>

<center>
<b>EXTRAPOLATE COORDINATES</b>
<p>Program: COOVEL
</center>
<hr width="100%">

<a name="ENVIRONMENT"   default="%% %%"></a>
<a name="CAMPAIGN"      default=""></a>
<a name="SESSION_TABLE" default="SESSIONS"></a>
<a name="YR4_INFO"      default="$Y+0"></a>
<a name="SES_INFO"      default="$S+0"></a>
<a name="USR_INFO"      default="${USER}"></a>

<p><b>GENERAL DESCRIPTION</b>
<p>
The purpose of program COOVEL is to propagate a given set of station
coordinates from a reference epoch to the epoch of the GPS observations
using the corresponding station velocities. The station velocities may
stem from
<ul>
<li>an official reference frame (e.g., ITRF2000). A SINEX file with these
    information may be transformed into Bernese format using the program
    <a href="PGMLST.HLP#SNX2NQ0">SNX2NQ0</a>.</li>
<li>a velocity estimation by program <a href="PGMLST.HLP#ADDNEQ2">ADDNEQ2</a>.
    Make sure that you have velocities for all stations in the coordinate
    file.</li>
<li>the NUVEL-1 or NUVEL-1A no-net-rotation plate motion model provided by
    the Bernese program <a href="PGMLST.HLP#NUVELO">NUVELO</a>.</li>
</ul>
If you have several sources of velocities you can use the program
<a href="PGMLST.HLP#CRDMERGE">CRDMERGE</a> to merge them.

<p><hr>

<b>COOVEL 1: Filenames</b>

<a name="SHOWGEN" default="1"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL FILES</b>
<p><b>Show all general files:</b>
This program does not need general files. If you check this box, the currently
active campaign, session and session table are displayed.

<br><br>

<a name="CRDINP" default=""></a>
<p><b>INPUT FILE</b>
<p><b>Input coordinate file:</b>
Select the name of the input coordinate file.

<p><i>Caution:</i>
Please make sure that the input coordinate file contains
the epoch information in its header.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.CRD">Example</a>

<a name="VELOCI" default=""></a>
<p><b>Input velocity file:</b>
Select the name of a velocity file which contains the velocities for the
stations contained in the coordinate file specified above.

<p><i>Remark:</i>
For coordinates without velocities in this file the
coordinates are propagated with zero velocity. The epoch of the resulting
coordinate file may no longer correspond to the actual epoch of these
coordinates.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.VEL">Example</a>

<br><br>

<a name="REFDAT" default="$YMD_STR+0"></a>
<a name="REFTIM" default="00 00 00"></a>
<p><b>REFERENCE EPOCH</b>
<p>Specify the epoch to which the coordinates in the selected input coordinate
file shall be propagated.

<br><br>

<a name="CRDOUT" default=""></a>
<p><b>RESULT FILE</b>
<p><b>Output coordinate file:</b>
The resulting file will contain the station coordinates from the sites of
the input coordinate file referring to the reference epoch specified above.
The new epoch of the coordinates will be written into the header of the file.

<p><i>Caution:</i>
For coordinates without velocities specified in the
velocity file the coordinates are propagated with zero velocity. The epoch
of the resulting coordinate file may no longer correspond to the actual epoch
of these coordinates.

<br><br>

<a name="SYSODEF" default="1"></a>
<a name="SYSOUT"  default="COOVEL"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL OUTPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Program output:</b>
You can choose to have the program output written to a separate file for each
program run (checkbox marked), or specify a common name for all program runs.
<br>
If you mark the checkbox, the filename will correspond to the program name
with an extension containing a counter (Lnn), which is automatically
incremented for each program run. If the counter reaches the maximum value, it
is automatically reset, and existing files will be overwritten.
The maximum value can be set in
<b>Menu &gt; Configure &gt; Program Names</b>, option "Maximum program output
file number".
<br>
If the checkbox is unmarked, you have to specify a name for the program
output file. This allows to characterize the program run, e.g., by using the
day and year (<tt>$YD+0</tt>) in the filename.

<a name="ERRMRG" default="0"></a>
<a name="SYSERR" default="ERROR"></a>
<p><b>Error messages:</b>
You can choose to have error messages written into the program's output
file (see above), or specify a separate file to which error messages are
written.

<br><br>

<a name="TITLE" default=""></a>
<p><b>TITLE</b>
<p>
This title line will be printed as header comment into the program output
to document the program run. The title should characterize the program run by,
e.g., giving the most important options used and the session.

<p><hr>

</body>
</html>
